00:00:20.659 --> 00:00:23.200
JEFF GORE: Today, what we want
to do is focus more explicitly

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:24.890
on bacterial chemotaxis.

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:26.560
Of course, a
discussion that we had

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:29.330
on Thursday about "Life
at Low Reynolds Numbers"

00:00:29.330 --> 00:00:31.290
is certainly very
relevant to this question

00:00:31.290 --> 00:00:34.390
of how bacteria are
maybe able to find food

00:00:34.390 --> 00:00:36.380
or what constraints
they're faced in trying

00:00:36.380 --> 00:00:37.530
to solve this problem.

00:00:37.530 --> 00:00:39.900
Today, we're going to
discuss in more depth

00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:43.570
this idea of the biased random
walk that runs and tumbles

00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:46.240
that we talked about on
Thursday, that allow bacteria

00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:49.680
to swim towards attractants
and away from repellents.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:51.530
But in particular,
there's something

00:00:51.530 --> 00:00:56.330
that is rather subtle about the
particular biased random walk

00:00:56.330 --> 00:00:58.310
that bacteria implement.

00:00:58.310 --> 00:01:01.170
Now, the way that you
might kind of naively

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:03.170
imagine that this
thing would work

00:01:03.170 --> 00:01:06.100
is that you would just have
this tumbling frequency be

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:10.850
a function of the concentration
of the attractant, for example.

00:01:10.850 --> 00:01:14.210
And that indeed would allow
you to swim or to execute

00:01:14.210 --> 00:01:16.650
a biased random walk
towards, say, food sources,

00:01:16.650 --> 00:01:18.910
towards attractants,
but it would not

00:01:18.910 --> 00:01:22.760
be effective over a very
wide range of concentrations.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:25.697
However, if you experimentally
ask, how well can bacteria

00:01:25.697 --> 00:01:27.280
swim towards
attractants, it turns out

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:29.690
they can respond over
five orders of magnitude

00:01:29.690 --> 00:01:32.700
of concentration of these
attractants, which is really

00:01:32.700 --> 00:01:36.760
quite incredible, if you think
about the engineering challenge

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:42.950
that these little one-micron
cells are able to overcome.

00:01:42.950 --> 00:01:45.690
And the basic way that
they do this is they

00:01:45.690 --> 00:01:48.840
implement what's essentially
equivalent to integral feedback

00:01:48.840 --> 00:01:51.630
in the context of engineering,
where it turns out

00:01:51.630 --> 00:01:55.081
that the steady-state tumbling
frequency, so the frequency

00:01:55.081 --> 00:01:56.580
of which they'd
execute one of these

00:01:56.580 --> 00:02:00.414
tumbles that randomizes their
motion, that displays what's

00:02:00.414 --> 00:02:01.580
known as perfect adaptation.

00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:08.770
It's not a function of the
concentration of-- if you have

00:02:08.770 --> 00:02:10.746
a constant concentration
of an attractant,

00:02:10.746 --> 00:02:12.120
then it's not a
function of that.

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:14.720
Of course, changes in
concentrations it responds to,

00:02:14.720 --> 00:02:18.790
but somehow, E. coli and
many other microorganisms

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:21.900
are able to implement this
very clever thing where

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:24.540
the steady-state frequency
of tumbling, of changing

00:02:24.540 --> 00:02:26.040
direction, is somehow
not a function

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:29.290
of the overall
attractant concentration.

00:02:29.290 --> 00:02:33.010
Now, that's already an
interesting, I think,

00:02:33.010 --> 00:02:34.470
phenomenon.

00:02:34.470 --> 00:02:37.040
And in some ways,
you can think of it

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:39.550
as some kind of
robustness, because there

00:02:39.550 --> 00:02:41.990
is some way in which this
tumbling frequency is

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:47.372
robust against constant changes
in the level of attractants.

00:02:47.372 --> 00:02:48.830
And it's that
aspect, I think, that

00:02:48.830 --> 00:02:51.160
makes this example both
rather subtle but also

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:54.610
quite confusing, because
it's the phenomenon

00:02:54.610 --> 00:02:56.430
of perfect adaptation
that already

00:02:56.430 --> 00:02:58.630
has some aspects of
robustness, but it's

00:02:58.630 --> 00:03:00.480
this phenomenon of
perfect adaptation

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:03.679
that is robust against changes
in concentrations of proteins,

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:05.970
for example, the concentration
of the protein [? key ?]

00:03:05.970 --> 00:03:08.650
R that we're going
to talk about.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:10.960
So I think that this
is in some ways maybe

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:15.120
the prettiest
example that we have

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:17.100
of this principle
of robustness, but I

00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:19.180
think it's also in
some ways the most

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:22.840
tricky to wrap your head around,
because it's sort of robustness

00:03:22.840 --> 00:03:25.340
of a robustness in some ways.

00:03:28.665 --> 00:03:30.170
All right.

00:03:30.170 --> 00:03:33.640
So our goal for today is
going to be to make sure

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:38.120
that we understand the challenge
that E. coli are facing

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:41.340
and then to try to understand
the genetic circuit

00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:45.370
that they use in order to
overcome this challenge.

00:03:45.370 --> 00:03:48.450
So what I'm going to do for
the next hour and 15 minutes

00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:51.460
is we're going to leave
this network up on the board

00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:54.910
so that any time that
you're confused about what

00:03:54.910 --> 00:03:58.990
is R, B, Z, Y, so
forth, you can kind of

00:03:58.990 --> 00:04:03.480
look up here and remind
yourself what this thing is.

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:05.910
But hopefully, the
reading from last night

00:04:05.910 --> 00:04:09.290
will help you in
following what's going on.

00:04:09.290 --> 00:04:12.855
There are a fair number of
letters, I will admit it.

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:18.930
So first, I just
want to make sure

00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:20.410
that we're all
kind of remembering

00:04:20.410 --> 00:04:24.200
the basic phenomenon
that we're trying

00:04:24.200 --> 00:04:28.300
to study, which is this idea of
consecutive runs and tumbles.

00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:33.170
So this random walk is really
composed of what you might call

00:04:33.170 --> 00:04:36.630
or what we do call runs,
where the bacteria goes sort

00:04:36.630 --> 00:04:38.430
of straight and
then tumbles, which

00:04:38.430 --> 00:04:40.240
they randomize their motion.

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:52.020
So this is runs and tumbles,
where bacteria, they

00:04:52.020 --> 00:05:02.970
go semi-straight for of order
a second-- order one second--

00:05:02.970 --> 00:05:05.420
and this is the run.

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:07.620
Then, they have
this tumbling that

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:15.460
might last about one second,
so a 0.1 second tumble,

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:19.890
over which the motion is
sort of random in this axis

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:22.750
of the orientation.

00:05:22.750 --> 00:05:25.360
And then, they kind of
go in a new direction

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:29.870
and then tumble again and then
new direction and so forth.

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:37.920
So it's runs
followed by tumbles.

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:44.470
Now, the thing that
changes depending

00:05:44.470 --> 00:05:46.450
on whether the cells
are sensing that they're

00:05:46.450 --> 00:05:49.730
moving up or down, say,
an attractant gradient

00:05:49.730 --> 00:05:53.730
is the frequency of
those tumbles, i.e.

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:55.870
how long are the runs?

00:05:55.870 --> 00:05:58.090
I said that they're
around one second,

00:05:58.090 --> 00:06:04.020
but this will vary depending
upon whether bacteria

00:06:04.020 --> 00:06:05.540
sense that things
are getting better

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:06.706
or things are getting worse.

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:14.440
Can somebody remind us how
the bacteria actually execute

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:16.525
one of these tumble motions?

00:06:20.728 --> 00:06:21.228
Yes?

00:06:21.228 --> 00:06:24.180
AUDIENCE: They have this other
motors-- they have mini-motors

00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:25.902
in their flagella
and they usually

00:06:25.902 --> 00:06:28.680
all spin one way, which I
think is counterclockwise.

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:29.680
JEFF GORE: That's right.

00:06:29.680 --> 00:06:32.040
I always have trouble--
so the runs are indeed

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:34.414
when these things are
rotating counterclockwise.

00:06:34.414 --> 00:06:35.038
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:06:35.038 --> 00:06:37.585
And one of them can
decide to switch

00:06:37.585 --> 00:06:39.910
and start turning clockwise.

00:06:39.910 --> 00:06:42.015
And what it does, it just
sort of-- I don't know.

00:06:42.015 --> 00:06:43.890
I just imagine it throws
the whole motor off.

00:06:43.890 --> 00:06:44.860
JEFF GORE: Exactly.

00:06:44.860 --> 00:06:52.920
And the flagella in the context
of-- so we have our E. coli.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:56.530
The velocity is of order,
say, 30 microns per second.

00:07:00.002 --> 00:07:01.960
Now, they have these
flagella that are actually

00:07:01.960 --> 00:07:04.650
distributed-- the motors
are actually distributed

00:07:04.650 --> 00:07:06.010
across the entire cell.

00:07:06.010 --> 00:07:07.580
So it's not just on the back.

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:09.690
But then, these individual
filaments kind of

00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:12.450
come together towards
the back and then

00:07:12.450 --> 00:07:16.400
they have this corkscrew shape.

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:18.150
When these things
are all rotating

00:07:18.150 --> 00:07:20.050
in the counterclockwise
direction,

00:07:20.050 --> 00:07:23.870
that corresponds to a run,
when there's directed motion.

00:07:23.870 --> 00:07:28.230
But then if one of
them goes clockwise,

00:07:28.230 --> 00:07:30.207
the bundle falls apart.

00:07:30.207 --> 00:07:32.290
And indeed, there are some
very nice movies online

00:07:32.290 --> 00:07:34.930
where you can see that when
they're going clockwise,

00:07:34.930 --> 00:07:39.030
you see that the flagella are
kind of doing crazy things

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:41.650
and that causes this
thing to kind of tumble

00:07:41.650 --> 00:07:42.650
in a random orientation.

00:07:42.650 --> 00:07:44.350
So it randomizes its direction.

00:07:56.910 --> 00:08:00.070
Now, one thing that
we did not talk

00:08:00.070 --> 00:08:03.920
about in the context of this
low Reynolds number motion

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:06.690
was the question of
how hard you would

00:08:06.690 --> 00:08:10.660
have to pull in
order to get a cell

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:12.300
to go 30 microns per second.

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:20.440
Now, remember, we're in the
low Reynolds number regime,

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:23.767
where the force
you have to apply

00:08:23.767 --> 00:08:25.600
is in general proportional
to this velocity.

00:08:29.050 --> 00:08:33.740
And this thing is very
much not a sphere,

00:08:33.740 --> 00:08:39.200
but if it were a sphere, for
a sphere, the proportionality

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:45.240
constant is this 6 pi eta
av, where a here is again

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:45.850
the radius.

00:08:50.050 --> 00:08:52.710
Now, regardless of
the precise shape,

00:08:52.710 --> 00:08:57.080
you'll always get for the low
Reynolds regime something that

00:08:57.080 --> 00:08:59.620
looks vaguely like this, where
this is going to the longest

00:08:59.620 --> 00:09:03.560
linear dimension and this here
depends on the precise geometry

00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:04.250
of the object.

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:11.210
And so just-- it's
useful to try to get

00:09:11.210 --> 00:09:13.760
a sense of order of magnitude.

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:18.030
How large are these forces
that we're talking about?

00:09:18.030 --> 00:09:22.040
In particular,
how hard would you

00:09:22.040 --> 00:09:25.079
have to pull a cell
in order to get

00:09:25.079 --> 00:09:26.370
it to go 30 microns per second?

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:32.370
Now, of course then,
there's a question.

00:09:32.370 --> 00:09:35.770
What's roughly the scale that
we should be thinking about?

00:09:35.770 --> 00:09:39.730
Right now, a newton is the scale
that's for macroscopic objects.

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:42.870
So you'd say, OK, probably
not going to be up that large.

00:09:42.870 --> 00:09:45.110
Then, on the other
scale, we can think

00:09:45.110 --> 00:09:49.240
about the forces that
can be applied or exerted

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:51.330
by individual molecular motors.

00:09:55.450 --> 00:09:58.644
Has anybody studied this at all?

00:09:58.644 --> 00:10:00.430
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:03.380
JEFF GORE: Right,
order of picanewtons.

00:10:03.380 --> 00:10:09.630
So force for a
molecular motor is going

00:10:09.630 --> 00:10:12.108
to be of order picanewtons.

00:10:14.860 --> 00:10:17.780
Now, there's a
simple way to kind of

00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:22.870
get at why this might actually
be, because what is it

00:10:22.870 --> 00:10:27.110
that powers many of
these molecular motors?

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:28.706
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:28.706 --> 00:10:30.330
JEFF GORE: Yeah, so
it's often-- you're

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:33.470
thinking of maybe the motors
that operate in a membrane.

00:10:33.470 --> 00:10:35.200
And then, there might
be some difference

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:37.660
in a gradient, so a
difference in concentration

00:10:37.660 --> 00:10:39.410
across that membrane
and that can actually

00:10:39.410 --> 00:10:41.609
power, for example, rotation.

00:10:41.609 --> 00:10:43.150
We're going to talk
a little bit more

00:10:43.150 --> 00:10:45.650
about this in the context
of the flagella motor,

00:10:45.650 --> 00:10:51.370
because this is one of only
a few known rotary motors.

00:10:51.370 --> 00:10:53.900
I'm just going to write this
down so that I don't forget

00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:55.133
to say something about it.

00:10:58.300 --> 00:10:59.610
But in this case--

00:10:59.610 --> 00:11:00.294
AUDIENCE: ATP?

00:11:00.294 --> 00:11:01.210
JEFF GORE: ATP, right?

00:11:01.210 --> 00:11:04.190
So in many cases, what
happens is that you have,

00:11:04.190 --> 00:11:06.280
for example, kinesin or myosin.

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:11.040
These are motors that walk along
some track and in many cases,

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:17.390
each step corresponds to a
single ATP being hydrolyzed.

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:20.880
And so given that,
there's some maximal force

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:23.540
that you can imagine
such a motor applying.

00:11:23.540 --> 00:11:25.550
So for example-- and what
might it depend upon?

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:35.589
AUDIENCE: The energy of
ATP hydrolysis [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:35.589 --> 00:11:36.630
JEFF GORE: Ah, very good.

00:11:36.630 --> 00:11:40.474
So we have delta G for say, ATP.

00:11:40.474 --> 00:11:42.390
And there's going to be
a length scale, right?

00:11:42.390 --> 00:11:44.139
And what's going to
be the relevant length

00:11:44.139 --> 00:11:46.878
scale in the case of, for
example, a motor like kinesin?

00:11:46.878 --> 00:11:49.392
AUDIENCE: The flagella, I guess?

00:11:49.392 --> 00:11:51.850
JEFF GORE: Well, kinesin is
not walking along the flagella,

00:11:51.850 --> 00:11:56.060
but in this case, kinesin is
walking along microtubules,

00:11:56.060 --> 00:11:57.040
for example.

00:11:57.040 --> 00:11:59.230
So you're right that
we need a length scale,

00:11:59.230 --> 00:12:02.560
because this is going to have
some units of say, picanewton

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:08.770
nanometers-- oops,
that's an Nm--

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:13.070
and we want to get a picanewton
so we're going to need a length

00:12:13.070 --> 00:12:14.495
scale to divide by, right?

00:12:14.495 --> 00:12:16.480
AUDIENCE: So how long
you move each time?

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:17.480
JEFF GORE: That's right.

00:12:17.480 --> 00:12:19.896
It's kind of the distance that
this thing's moving, right?

00:12:19.896 --> 00:12:22.590
So indeed, what happens
in the case of kinesin

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:25.480
is that they take steps
with what are called "heads"

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:27.700
but we can think of them
as "feet" if we want.

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:30.660
So each step is in this
case eight nanometers.

00:12:30.660 --> 00:12:37.760
For example, delta L for kinesin
is equal to eight nanometers.

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:39.510
You don't need to know
this, but just it's

00:12:39.510 --> 00:12:41.025
useful to have some
sense of scale.

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:47.320
Now, of course,
delta G of ATP, this

00:12:47.320 --> 00:12:52.210
depends upon the concentrations
of the reactants,

00:12:52.210 --> 00:12:54.420
of the products, and so forth.

00:12:54.420 --> 00:12:59.320
But this thing might be of
order 100 picanewton nanometers.

00:13:04.234 --> 00:13:05.900
Now, depending on
conditions, maybe it's

00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:08.330
70, but of order here.

00:13:08.330 --> 00:13:09.980
And indeed, what
this tells us is

00:13:09.980 --> 00:13:13.280
that just based on what
we've said right now, even

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:16.140
without building any fancy
microscopes to measure

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:18.200
how much force these
things can apply,

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:21.957
you can see that the maximum
force it could possibly apply

00:13:21.957 --> 00:13:24.040
would be something on the
order of delta G divided

00:13:24.040 --> 00:13:26.203
by the length that it's pulling.

00:13:28.750 --> 00:13:33.590
Otherwise, you could make
a perpetual motion machine.

00:13:33.590 --> 00:13:36.430
So this-- well,
maybe what we'll do

00:13:36.430 --> 00:13:38.149
if we want to make
our math simpler,

00:13:38.149 --> 00:13:39.440
we could say this is around 80.

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:40.440
It's of order there.

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:43.700
But the point is that this
is of order 10 picanewtons,

00:13:43.700 --> 00:13:45.100
so it's kind of
picanewton scale.

00:13:49.471 --> 00:13:50.004
All right.

00:13:50.004 --> 00:13:52.420
So given this, it's interesting
to ask, how hard would you

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:53.540
have to pull?

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:57.540
So how big is a kinesin model
going to be, this protein?

00:14:00.715 --> 00:14:02.090
AUDIENCE: About
eight nanometers.

00:14:02.090 --> 00:14:03.350
JEFF GORE: Yeah, right,
about eight nanometers.

00:14:03.350 --> 00:14:05.183
Of course, it's kind
of long, spindly things

00:14:05.183 --> 00:14:07.330
like my skinny legs,
right, but let's

00:14:07.330 --> 00:14:10.710
indeed going to be
around that scale,

00:14:10.710 --> 00:14:16.970
whereas the cell is one micron
wide, multiple microns long, so

00:14:16.970 --> 00:14:18.210
much, much larger.

00:14:18.210 --> 00:14:21.655
We'll draw a little--
here's a kinesin in there.

00:14:24.650 --> 00:14:26.350
It's even smaller than that.

00:14:26.350 --> 00:14:27.704
Kinesin's small.

00:14:27.704 --> 00:14:29.620
Now, the question is,
how much force would you

