00:17:13.473 --> 00:17:16.740
do the equations here, right?

00:17:16.740 --> 00:17:19.891
The force, it's around 20.

00:17:19.891 --> 00:17:21.599
In units of picanewton
nanometer seconds,

00:17:21.599 --> 00:17:25.339
I told you that the eta is
around 10 to the minus 9.

00:17:25.339 --> 00:17:25.839
All right.

00:17:25.839 --> 00:17:29.130
And the radius, what
radius do you want to use?

00:17:29.130 --> 00:17:29.950
AUDIENCE: A micron.

00:17:29.950 --> 00:17:30.940
JEFF GORE: A micron.

00:17:30.940 --> 00:17:32.580
So do we write a 1 here?

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:34.570
Do we write what?

00:17:34.570 --> 00:17:36.550
10 to the 3 because
I already told you

00:17:36.550 --> 00:17:38.890
that this was in units where
everything is picanewtons

00:17:38.890 --> 00:17:40.180
nanometers seconds.

00:17:40.180 --> 00:17:42.580
And velocity, this
is again per second.

00:17:42.580 --> 00:17:47.740
So this is three times 10 to
the 4, because that's how many

00:17:47.740 --> 00:17:50.770
nanometers per second.

00:17:50.770 --> 00:17:55.489
And this gets us to around--
that's 10 to the seven.

00:17:55.489 --> 00:17:57.030
We're going to have
to divide by 100,

00:17:57.030 --> 00:18:05.627
so this is 60 divided by 100--
so less than a picanewton.

00:18:08.490 --> 00:18:12.430
So this is really
pretty surprising.

00:18:12.430 --> 00:18:17.090
And again, this is a reflection
of the wonders of low Reynolds

00:18:17.090 --> 00:18:18.300
numbers kind of behavior.

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:21.278
So it's somewhere here.

00:18:24.080 --> 00:18:24.580
Yes?

00:18:24.580 --> 00:18:26.540
AUDIENCE: So since
there are many flagella,

00:18:26.540 --> 00:18:29.970
is it telling us--
