01:16:40.587 --> 01:16:41.170
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:16:41.170 --> 01:16:43.620
JEFF GORE: OK, good, all right.

01:16:43.620 --> 01:16:47.210
So if we have some
protein that is negatively

01:16:47.210 --> 01:16:52.460
autoregulating itself,
then this adds robustness.

01:16:52.460 --> 01:16:54.860
And this is because
we can say, all right,

01:16:54.860 --> 01:16:59.330
this is the degradation term,
alpha x, the production term.

01:16:59.330 --> 01:17:03.340
And the limit of being perfect,
sharp, negative autoregulation

01:17:03.340 --> 01:17:04.140
looks like this.

01:17:04.140 --> 01:17:05.723
So this is the
production/degradation.

01:17:09.020 --> 01:17:11.350
And here, this might be beta.

01:17:11.350 --> 01:17:14.600
This is a k.

01:17:14.600 --> 01:17:18.060
Then, what we can
talk about is how

01:17:18.060 --> 01:17:23.000
the steady-state concentration
of x here is going to be k.

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:27.620
And this thing is robust to
variations in some things,

01:17:27.620 --> 01:17:29.290
but not other things.

01:17:29.290 --> 01:17:31.870
For example, it's robust
to changes in alpha.

01:17:31.870 --> 01:17:32.899
That changes the slope.

01:17:32.899 --> 01:17:34.940
It's robust to changes in
beta, because that just

01:17:34.940 --> 01:17:39.030
brings it up and down, but it's
not robust to changes in k.

01:17:39.030 --> 01:17:42.360
So I think that any time
that if you are confused

01:17:42.360 --> 01:17:46.060
about robustness, in particular
thinking about robustness

01:17:46.060 --> 01:17:47.530
in the context of
chemotaxis gets

01:17:47.530 --> 01:17:50.150
you confused because of perfect
adaptation being confusing,

01:17:50.150 --> 01:17:52.108
I think it's always good
to come back and think

01:17:52.108 --> 01:17:55.870
about this because this is the
most clear case where you can

01:17:55.870 --> 01:17:57.615
talk about-- this
is the robustness

01:17:57.615 --> 01:17:58.990
of the steady-state
concentration

01:17:58.990 --> 01:18:03.900
of some protein against
variations in alpha and beta,

01:18:03.900 --> 01:18:04.950
but not against k.

01:18:04.950 --> 01:18:09.250
So it reminds you that it's
not that this level of x

01:18:09.250 --> 01:18:11.760
is robust against
everything, but it's

01:18:11.760 --> 01:18:12.960
robust against some things.

01:18:12.960 --> 01:18:14.668
And you can make sense
of which things it

01:18:14.668 --> 01:18:16.950
should be robust against,
which things not.

